" Counting partitions is algorithmically and computationally different from existence verification: it is a stronger result (a nonzero count implies verification), but requires large-scale distributed Arm CPU infrastructure rather than commodity GPU hardware","A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
 None of these frameworks demonstrated exhaustive existence verification beyond 10 11 on a single commodity device; the obstacles preventing this (VRAM exhaustion from monolithic prime-table storage and the resulting inability to scale the verified range) are documented in our prior work [4],"A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
 GoldbachGPU v1,"A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
"Our prior work [ 4] resolved the VRAM ceiling via a segmented double-sieve: the prime table was replaced by a fixed 14 MB segment bitset, regenerated per segment on the CPU and transferred to the GPU","A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
 This enabled exhaustive verification to 10 12 on an RTX 3070,"A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
" However, scaling to additional GPUs was limited by the CPU sieve: at N = 1010, a single H100 and a single RTX 3090 took essentially the same wall- clock time ( ≈19 s), confirming that GPU compute was not the bottleneck","A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
 The present work removes this bottleneck entirely by moving the sieve to the GPU,"A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
" 3 Systems Architecture The proposed framework transitions from a sequential, host-orchestrated loop to a fully decentralised, asynchronous multi-GPU pipeline","A Lock-Free, Fully GPU-Resident Architecture for the Verification of Goldbach’s Conjecture"
