" , t} if t >0 (1) where the subscript t refers to the increasing num- ber of turns, it refers to the user input and ot refers to the LLM’s output, formulated as: ot = Fθ(ht−1, it) (2) where Fθ refers to the LLM, and θ denotes its parameters",Game Development as Human-LLM Interaction
" Consequently, an LLM with pa- rameters θ seeks to maximize the likelihood:PT t=1 log pθ(ot|ht−1, it), where T refers to the to- tal number of interaction turns",Game Development as Human-LLM Interaction
 The distinction between ChatGE and a general multi-turn Human-LLM interaction lies in the spe- cialization of the input and output,Game Development as Human-LLM Interaction
 The user input it consists of instructions about their game con- cept and feedback to the LLM,Game Development as Human-LLM Interaction
 The LLM’s out- put ot includes both interactions with the user and code snippets to implement the user’s game con- cept in one turn,Game Development as Human-LLM Interaction
" To enable an LLM to function as a ChatGE, we instruct the LLM to perform the following processes in each turn: (1) Pscript: con- figure the game script segment based on the user’s input(Enclosed by <script></script>: in Fig- ure 1); (2) Pcode: generate the corresponding code snippet based on the game script segment(Enclosed by <code></code>: in Figure 1); (3) Putter: in- teract with the user, including guidance and feed- back(Enclosed by <utter></utter>: in Figure 1)",Game Development as Human-LLM Interaction
" For interaction and coding requirements, Pcode and Putter are essential",Game Development as Human-LLM Interaction
